<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-141-946  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 141 946.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer  March 1989 v22 n3 p50(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Current research in robotics and automation: an intelligentgrasping system. (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Allen, Peter; Michelman, Paul; Roberts, Kenneth.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Researchers at Columbia University's Department of ComputerScience develop a comprehensive grasping environment for robotsthat permits the robot to locate moving objects and pick them up,manipulate man-made objects and recognize unknown objects throughtouch.andP;  The work in dextrous manipulation also results in anintegrated programming environment that allows grasping andgrasping primitives within an overall robotic control andprogramming system.andP;  The system includesmultiple-degree-of-freedom manipulators, vision sensors anddextrous hands.andP;  System components include low-level systemprimitives as a base for hand control, a true hand-arm system,integrated tactile sensors on the fingertips providingforce-sensitive responses and Cartesian position information andsensing primitives that use joint position, tendon force andtactile array sensing for grasping and manipulation tasks.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Research and DevelopmentRobotics IndustryRobotsColumbia UniversityMaterials HandlingObject RecognitionManipulators.andO;Feature:   illustrationchartphotograph.andO;Caption:   Hardware overview. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>